article.headline: Creighton 88, N.C. Central 54
article.story: OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Reserve Kenton Walker scored a career-high 12 points and grabbed nine rebounds to lead Creighton past North Carolina Central 88-54 Thursday. The freshman, whose season-best effort was eight points entering the game, had eight points during a decisive 15-0 second-half run that helped the 8-1 Bluejays separate from the NCAA Division I newcomers. The Eagles (1-14), who played Division II basketball prior to this season, stayed within striking distance of Creighton until early in the second half. But a pair of dunks by Walker ignited the surge that sent the Jays to their seventh home win of the season. Creighton led 40-30 at the break after holding the Eagles without a field goal for more than six minutes late in the first half. North Carolina Central trailed by nine after a dunk by Bluejay P'Allen Stinnett with 8:23 left before intermission but rallied with seven straight points. A steal and layup by Bryan Ayala, who had 17 first-half points, pulled the Eagles within 28-26 with 6:49 left in the half. But that was the last basket for North Carolina Central until Charles Futrell scored eight seconds before halftime. Creighton extended its lead to 18 early in the second half before pulling away with its big run. Kenny Lawson finished with a team-high 13 points for the Jays, who outscored North Carolina Central 48-24 in the second half. Ayala had a season-best 26 points to lead all scorers. But he couldn't stop the Eagles, who have been outscored by an average of 33 points per game, from dropping to 0-14 on the road.
